}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 133-138.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The three theological virtues sing their appeal to Beatrice, requesting that she \softline
unveil her mouth.  The moment recalls an experience recorded in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 .  'Here it is necessary \softline
to know that the eyes of wisdom are her demonstrations, by which truth is seen with the greatest \softline
certainty, and her smiles are her persuasions, in which the inner light of wisdom [Sapienza] is \softline
revealed behind a kind of veil; and in each of them is felt the highest joy of blessedness, which is \softline
the greatest good of paradise.  This joy cannot be found in anything here below except by looking \softline
into [her] eyes and upon her smile' (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Conv}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . III.xv.2-3, tr. Lansing).  It is important to know that \softline
these words are directed to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 another}{\plain \fs24 \f1  lady, also known as Wisdom, in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , namely the \softline
Lady Philosophy, the one who came as the replacement for the then supposedly less worthy \softline
Beatrice.  That Dante clearly revisits that passage from }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  here is a fairly common belief \softline
among current discussants of this one.  Only a few (e.g., Mazzoni [{\u8220\'93}}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  Canto XXXI,{\u8221\'94} in \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis Scaligera}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (Florence: Le Monnier, 1965)], pp. 90-95; Giacalone [comm. to vv. \softline
136-138]), however, realize that Dante wants to separate the sort of affection he felt for the lady 
he celebrated in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Convivio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  then from that which he feels for the lady he celebrates here and now.  \softline
Further, the allegory operative then (eyes as demonstrations, mouth as persuasions, of the \softline
abstraction philosophy) is nowhere evident here, where we now find only the smile unveiled.  In \softline
her eyes Dante has just now seen what he can currently understand of Christ's two natures; in her \softline
smile he perceives that he is loved with the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 etterno piacer}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (eternal beauty -- }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXIX.32) that \softline
is reflected from her lips.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 138.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 seconda bellezza}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (second beauty) of Beatrice also may remind the reader of the \softline
'corollary' or extra gift that Matelda bestowed upon the three poets at the end of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
XXVIII.136.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 139-145.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 luce etterna}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (eternal living light) that is God has its }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 etterno piacer}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (eternal \softline
beauty) reflected in Beatrice, her loveliness the mirror of the beauty of God.  This direct address \softline
of Beatrice's smile (which seems -- intentionally, we must believe -- to be represented as an object \softline
illuminated fully by God's light) sounds so much like an invocation that it apparently fooled at \softline
least one reader into taking it as one.  See Marina De Fazio ("}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXIX," in  }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Dante's \softline
"Divine Comedy," Introductory Readings II: "Purgatorio,"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  ed. Tibor Wlassics [}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Lectura Dantis \softline
(virginiana)}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , 12, supplement, Charlottesville: University of Virginia, 1993]), p. 434.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab This passage is reminiscent of that in}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1  Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXVIII.139-148, the description of the \softline
smiles of recognition on the part of Virgil and of Statius when they discover that Eden represents \softline
the true Golden Age.  No pagan poet, no matter how deeply inspired by drinking of the Castalian \softline
spring on Parnassus, could have written of the meaning of his vision of the Golden Age in a way \softline
that could come near to equaling what this Christian poet (by virtue of his faith, not of his talent), \softline
having now drunk of Lethe, can tell of God's love in making his first human creature innocent and \softline
allowing His creature a chance to regain that lost innocence, which is what Dante has been \softline
allowed to accomplish here, while still in the flesh, and what he will finally accomplish after his \softline
death. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
